metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #644
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Divide by Circle #503
metadata.description:
An experiment with subdivision, cubes, and a circle.
There are many parameters and special features.
Click to randomize divisions with the same settings.
Unminted editions over 100 will be burnt after 24 hours.

By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel
Made with JavaScript and Three.js

Live Mode Controls
1 - Save 2048x2048 png with SSAA
2 - Toggle noise
3 - Toggle animation
4 - Randomize every 10 seconds

metadata.name: Celebration in Times of Measure #230
metadata.description:
Intentionally developed by placing constraints on the process.

Everything is generated by code written in P5js.

Press '1' for the default, textured version
Press '2' to add outlines and see the form structure

Press '3' to see a flat, untextured version
Press '4' to add outlines (flat version)

Press 'e' to end/skip the initial animation
Press 'r' to restart/replay the animation
Press 's' to save current image (in live view)

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: The Hum of Cyber Forest #148
metadata.description:
The forest exists as a noise, a hum of ever-changing states. 
The forest is chaos. 
The forest is technological, as it is filled with an uninterrupted seething of information, the exchange of pollen dust.

The rhythmic song of a cyborg shaman mingling with this noise evokes disintegrating, pixelated visions.

Rhythms of tree trunks are made with a help of DALL¬∑E mini neural network and were inspired by surrealistic painters.
Thanks Yulikolay for helping. The dithering code was inspired by a number of examples, links to which are indicated in the work‚Äôs code.
